David Njoku has been an afterthought this season as the TE22 in fantasy points per game. Njoku hasn't been a high-end target earner this season. He has only a 13.2% target share despite having a 75.2 % route share. He has only produced 39 receiving yards per game (1.14 yards per route run) with a 15.4% first-read share. Njoku is still searching for his first red zone look of the season. He hasn't finished higher than TE15 in weekly scoring in any week. Maybe the standout game comes this week, but I doubt it. Detroit has allowed the 12th-most receiving yards and the fourth-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Kyle Pitts is the TE16 in fantasy points per game with one TE1 finish in weekly scoring this season (TE7). He's a full-time player in the Falcons' offense with an 87.1% route share, a 17.9% target share, 45 receiving yards per game (1.34 yards per route run), and a 16.9% first-read share. This week, he has another plus schematic matchup. The Commanders have utilized single high with 55.8% of their defensive snaps. Against single-high, Pitts has seen his target share increase to 19.6% and this first-read share stays stable at 16.7%. Pitts could easily be a strong TE1 this season. The Commanders have allowed the highest yards per reception and the tenth-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

With every passing week, Harold Fannin Jr. looks more like 2024 Isiah Likely. The standout Week 1 performance gets further and further in the rearview. Over the last two weeks, he has averaged only 4.5 targets, four receptions, and 36.5 receiving yards. Fannin Jr. has settled into a 55.5% route share, which isn't great, while seeing a14% target share (24% target per route run rate) with 45.3 receiving yards per game (1.79 yards per route run) and a 17.9% first-read share. He hasn't had a red zone target since the one he saw in Week 1. Maybe he has a bounce-back game this week, but it's tough to bet on. Detroit has allowed the 12th-most receiving yards and the fourth-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

In his two games this season, Goedert has had an 87,.1% route share, a 16.4% target share, 1.26 yards per route run (38.5 receiving yards per game), and a 15.6% first-read share. He was a focal point of the game plan for Week 1, but last week, he had only two targets. He secured one for a 33-yard score. Goedert is a worrisome start this week against a secondary that has held tight ends to the ninth-fewest yards per reception and the seventh-fewest fantasy points per game.

Brenton Strange has one TE1 finish this season. That was last week as the TE7 in fantasy. He's still waiting for his first red zone target this season, so expecting a touchdown from him in any week right now is probably a fool's errand. Strange has a 65% route share with a 14.2% target share, 1.76 yards per route run (45.7 receiving yards per game), and a 14.4% first-read share. Strange isn't on the streaming radar this week. San Francisco has held tight ends to the eighth-lowest yards per reception and the tenth-fewest receiving yards.

Chig Okonkwo is the TE19 in fantasy points per game. He was the TE8 in weekly PPR scoring last week, which honestly says more about the state of the tight end position than it does about Okonkwo. Okonkwo has a 16.2% target share, 1.50 yards per route run, and a 17.2% first-read share. He hasn't seen a red zone target yet and has surpassed 40 receiving yards only once. Okonkwo isn't on the streaming radar this week. Houston has allowed the ninth-fewest receiving yards and fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Jonnu Smith is droppable. He's the TE19 in fantasy points per game, seeing a 14.8% target share with 21.7 receiving yards per game (1.18 yards per route run) and a 17.5% first-read share. He has only a 56.7% route share and a 0.8 aDOT. Minnesota ranks 19th in yards per reception and 16th in fantasy points per game allowed to tight ends.

Cade Otton has been a nothingburger in this offense. He'll get a bump from Mike Evans' injury, but I don't think that usage bump comes this week. Otton has had only a 6.1% target share, 0.30 yards per route run (8.3 receiving yards per game), and a 6.2% first-read share. Philly has kept tight ends in check, giving up the third-fewest fantasy points per game and the fifth-fewest receiving yards.

The arrival of Jonnu Smith has crushed Pat Freiermuth. He is the TE32 in fantasy points per game with a 48.5% route share, an 11.4% target share, 21.7 receiving yards per game (1.38 yards per route run), and an 11.1% first-read share. He is droppable in all redraft formats.

Cole Kmet is a viable streaming option this week. He has a 69.6% route share, a 7.3% target share, has averaged 23.3 receiving yards, and has had an 8,5% first-read share this season. All of those numbers could increase with Coltson Loveland out. Kmet has one red zone target this season. The Raiders rank 19th in receiving yards given up to tight ends, but they have also allowed the second-highest yards per reception to the position.

Mason Taylor began the season relatively quietly with only three targets and 25 receiving yards in his first two games. He has been a full-time player in each game, playing 78.3% of the snaps. Last week, he finally got more involved in the passing attack with a 13.9% target share, 18 receiving yards (0.62 yards per route run), and a 12.5% first-read share. Taylor has one red zone target this season. Taylor dealt with an ankle injury in camp and the preseason, so he could finally be inching closer to 100% which would explain the expanded role in Week 3. Taylor is a strong streaming candidate this week against a defense that has allowed the fourth-most receiving yards, the eighth-highest yards per reception, and the third-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Maxx was excellent in Week 3, tallying four solos, three assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Maxx is up to two sacks on the season, and this is the first game with the type of solo count we've come to expect from Crosby. Fire Maxx up as a top-five option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Aidan Hutchinson showed up in a big way on Monday Night Football, racking up two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and a key forced fumble. Aidan has a sack in back-to-back games and looks like he is about ready to produce a massive spike week. Continue to trust Hutchinson as a top-10 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Byron Young stayed hot in Week 3, reeling off four solos, two assists, one sack, and three tackles for loss. Young has a sack in every game this season and should be treated as a DL1 option until he cools down.

Brian Burns kept the good times rolling in Week 3, tallying five solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and two passes defended. Burns has been on fire to start the season, recording a sack in every game thus far for a total of four (second in the NFL). Continue to treat Burns as a top-10 option for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Furious George went off in Week 3, reeling off eight solos, two assists, one sack, three tackles for loss, and one pass defended. It was a monster performance that reminded us that a completely on Karlaftis is knocking on the door of the elite DL2 conversation for IDP. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Nik Bonitto was excellent in Week 3, tallying three solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Bonitto is up to three sacks on the season and is an easy DL1 play for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Jonathan Cooper was excellent in Week 3, tallying two solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Cooper is up to two sacks on the season and should be rostered in much more than two percent of Yahoo leagues. Cooper has double-digit sack upside and should be rostered where possible, especially if you play on a provider where he has DL eligibility. Add and start him where possible for a tasty Week 4 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Verse was excellent in Week 3, stacking four solos, two assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Verse had a slow start to the season, but finally has a sack on his ledger. Tap him as a DL2/3 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Dorance was excellent in Week 3, reeling off three solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Dorance now has a sack in three straight games to start the season and is staying busy in the solo department. We are not yet ready to anoint him a DL1 option; he needs to be considered a DL2 going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons. Add Armstrong everywhere, and start him universally while he's cooking.

Heyward was excellent in Week 3, racking up three solos, three assists, one sack, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. It was his first sack of the season, but he remains a DL2 option thanks to his activity in the tackle department. Treat him as such for Week 4.

Chris Jones showed up in Week 3, tallying one solo, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The sack was his first of the season, but there could be more good times ahead against a Baltimore Ravens offensive line that just 'allowed' Lamar Jackson to be sacked seven times on Monday Night Football. Tap Jones as a DT1/DL3 option for Week 4.

Diaby was excellent in Week 2, notching two solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The sack was his first of the season despite Yaya playing over 70 percent of the snaps each week. There will be more spike weeks for Diaby, but he remains more DL3/4 than DL2/3. Treat him as such despite a plus Week 4 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Montez showed up in Week 3, tallying two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. It has been a slow start for Sweat, but he has an excellent opportunity to keep the good times rolling in Week 4, thanks to a date with the Las Vegas Raiders.

Byron Murphy was at it again in Week 3, reeling off two solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Murphy is heating up and now has 2.5 sacks in his last two contests. His strong play has put him in the DL3 mix during the byes, and of course, he has worked his way into the DT1 conversation going forward. He has a plus matchup on tap against the Arizona Cardinals in Week 4 and should be added and started where needed.

Bryce Huff was excellent in Week 3, tallying two solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Huff has recorded a sack in back-to-back games while playing a rotational role. With Nick Bosa now lost for the season, Huff will be leaned on heavily by the 49ers, but we still can't expect much more than 60 to 70 percent of the snaps. Add and start Huff everywhere as a DL3 option for Week 4 and beyond.

AQM went bonkers on Monday Night Football, harassing the Ravens offense to the tune of three solos, one assist, 2.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. Al-Quadin has tallied 3.5 sacks in his last two games and is enjoying an expanded role with Marcus Davenport hitting IR. He turned some heads on Monday night and could be poised for a breakout season across from Aidan Hutchinson. Muhammad has a tasty matchup against the Cleveland Browns on deck for Week 4 and should be treated as a DL3 with DL2 upside.

Tyquan took advantage of the dream matchup against the Titans to the tune of three solos, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. Tyquan did his damage on 54 percent of the snaps, good for second-most on the edge for the Colts in Week 3. The Colts are using more than two edge rushers enough to give Tyquan some value, but with his non-zero production through the first two weeks of the season, the suggestion here is to leave Tyquan on benches for Week 4, even if you just added him. Look elsewhere for your Week 4 DL3/4.

Rumble big man, rumble. Jordan Davis was electric in Week 3, stacking four solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one blocked kick, and one touchdown. Davis reminded the world that he can be a game wrecker, too, even if Jalen Carter is the one most commonly brought up by analysts. Davis is an easy DT2 with DT1 upside who doubles as a DL4 option. There is indeed a place for him to start in DL leagues, especially with the New York Giants up twice in the next five weeks.

Maliek showed up in Week 3, racking up two solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. It was Collins' first sack of the season, so he is not someone you want to stick in lineups yet, even if you just added him this week. He should be on DT2 radars in DT leagues, but should be left on benches for Week 4. Look elsewhere for your Week 4 DL3/4.

Jenkins was excellent in Week 3, tallying two solos, four assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. It was the first sack of the season for Jenkins, but he belongs on the DT2 radar for the byes. He does have two solos in each game this season, so even those in DL leagues will want to stash (deep leagues) or add him to watchlists as a bye week option. Leave him benched for Week 4 despite the plus matchup against a Denver Broncos team surrendering the most fantasy points to the position.
White played just 24 percent of the snaps in Week 3 and should not be on redraft rosters unless you play in 32-team leagues. Look elsewhere for your Week 4 DL4.

AQM went bonkers on Monday Night Football, harassing the Ravens offense to the tune of three solos, one assist, 2.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. Al-Quadin has tallied 3.5 sacks in his last two games and is enjoying an expanded role with Marcus Davenport hitting IR. He turned some heads on Monday night and could be poised for a breakout season across from Aidan Hutchinson. Muhammad has a tasty matchup against the Cleveland Browns on deck for Week 4 and should be treated as a DL3 with DL2 upside.

Warner was at it again in Week 3, tallying five solos, six assists, and two passes defended against the Arizona Cardinals. Warner remains one of the most productive and consistent options in all of IDP. Tap him as a top-five option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Baun was excellent in Week 3, racking up three solos, four assists, one interception, and two passes defended against the Los Angeles Rams. Baun has recorded five or more solos in two of his three contests and should see more than enough volume in Week 4 to repeat the feat. Tap Baun as a top-15 option for a plus matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Jamien Sherwood was excellent against the Buccaneers, reeling off five solos and six assists. Sherwood now has at least five solos and five assists in back-to-back weeks, reminding the IDP world why he remains in the LB1 discussion. Treat him as just that for a plus Week 4 matchup against a struggling Miami Dolphins offense.

Dodson went off in Week 3, tallying 11 solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Dodson has had a stellar start to the season and is now tied for the NFL lead with 23 solo tackles through three contests. He has recorded at least six solos in each. Tap Dodson as an easy LB2 with LB1 upside for a plus matchup against the New York Jets on Monday Night Football.

Bobby Wagner went off in Week 3, exploding for six solos, five assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss against Pete Carroll and the Las Vegas Raiders. Wagner has recorded 10 or more total tackles in each game this season and remains one of the most consistent options at the position. Tap him as a top-15 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Jack Campbell went off on Monday night, stacking eight solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble against the Baltimore Ravens. Campbell has had a strong start to the season, recording four assists or more in each of his first two games before his Week 3 explosion. Campbell is an LB3 with matchup-based LB2 upside. Treat him as an LB2/3 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Quay was excellent in Week 3, racking up six solos, eight assists, and one pass defended. Quay has recorded six or more solos in two of his three contests and is inching closer to LB1 consideration. For now, continue to treat him as an elite LB2 option ahead of a tasty Week 4 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Bernard was excellent in Week 3, racking up five solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. The veteran linebacker remains a strong LB1 option and should be treated as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Robert Spillane went off in Week 3, tallying 10 solos, five assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Spillane was struggling in the solo department with New England, so this burst of production helps renew confidence in him going forward. It is still probably better to temper expectations for the season overall, but a tasty Week 4 opponent puts him back in the LB1 mix as a near must-start. Fire Spillane up as a top-15 option for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Schwesinger came to life in Week 3, stacking seven solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. It was a nice showing for the rookie, especially after he managed just five total solos over the first two weeks of the season. Start him as an LB3 with easy LB2 upside, thanks to a plus matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Bolton was excellent in Week 3, tallying six solos, eight assists, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Bolton has been a strong LB1 option through three weeks of the season, recording six or more solos in two of his three contests. He remains in the LB1 conversation for Week 4 and possesses considerable upside due to a date with Lamar Jackson. Start him where possible.

Alex Singleton showed up in Week 3, tallying four solos and eight assists. It is a step in the right direction for Singleton, but he has been a massive disappointment after being drafted as an LB1 this offseason. With that said, Spillane going off in Week 3 helped remind us not to sit our studs, but there is nothing wrong with temporarily downgrading them and plugging them into lineups (or not), accordingly. Singleton has failed to top four solos in any contest this season, and his only peripheral contribution thus far was a pass defended back in Week 1. He had six total solos coming into this contest, so we are not prepared to move him out of the LB3 realm prior to the byes. Start where possible as LB3 with LB2 upside for a tasty matchup against Cincinnati, but look elsewhere if you need LB1 or LB2 help.

Edumunds turned heads in Week 3, providing a vintage performance with six solos, nine assists, two interceptions, and two passes defended.  Edmunds was quiet in Week 1, but has now strung together back-to-back strong outings, putting him on the LB2 map for the byes. He is an LB2/3 option for Week 4, but temper your FAAB bids due to the Week 5 bye for the Chicago Bears.

Lavonte showed up in Week 3, racking up seven solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. David had a slow start to the season with just four total solos in the first two weeks, but this is a step in the right direction. He remains an LB2 option but can no longer be counted on for LB1 upside. Treat him as a top-25 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Kaden Ellis showed up in Week 3, tallying five solos, four assists, one sack, and three tackles for loss. Elliss was a slow starter to the season, totaling just five solos in the first two weeks of the season. Elliss has the talent to be counted as an elite LB2, but his slow start has dropped him to more of the LB2/3 range. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Washington Commanders.

Mack Wilson was excellent in Week 3, racking up six solos, six assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Wilson now has four or more solos in each of his games so far and is settling in nicely as an LB3 with LB2 upside. He will double as an LB2 option during the byes and should be rostered in most, if not all, competitive leagues. Make the add where available.

Rozeboom was excellent in Week 3, racking up six solos and three assists. Rozeboom has opened some eyes by generating six or more solos in two of his three contests so far, putting him in the LB2 mix with plus matchups. He has just that in Week 4 against the New England Patriots, so add and start Rozeboom where needed

Queen was excellent in Week 3, racking up six solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Queen remains a solid LB2 option and should be treated as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Pete Werner was excellent in Week 3, tallying seven solos, six assists, and one fumble recovery. Werner has had a strong start to the season, recording at least five solos in each game. Werner has solidified himself as an LB2 with LB1 upside and may even have LB1 appeal during some of the bye weeks. Werner should be rostered in all competitive leagues. Add and start Werner where possible ahead of a plus Week 4 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Sewell was excellent in place of T.J. Edwards, shining with six solos and five assists. Sewell turned heads in his Week 1 start with seven solos and two assists and has worked his way into must-start territory whenever T.J. Edwards or Tremaine Edmunds are sidelined. Start him in Week 4 against the Raiders if T.J. Edwards is out again.

Eric Wilson showed up in Week 3, racking up five solos, two assists, and one fumble recovery. Wilson has been known to provide steady production when given extended snaps, and with Blakr Cashman on IR until Week 7, Wilson should get plenty of run. Add and start Wilson where needed.

Watt finally got going in Week 3, racking up two solos, three assists, two sacks, two tackles for loss, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. The sacks were his first two of the season, but more good times should be on the way, possibly as soon as Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against Carson Wentz and the Minnesota Vikings. Start Watt as a top-10 option.

Pace was excellent in Week 3, reeling off nine solos and three assists. Pace is starting to heat up for the Vikings, and now has 16 solos in his last two contests. The production propels him back into the LB2 conversation, even with a quiet Week 1 on the ledger. Add Pace where possible as an LB2/3 option.

Lloyd was excellent in Week 3, racking up four solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Lloyd has been a disappointment for IDP managers, managing just six solos total in three weeks of action. He has salvaged some fantasy value thanks to contributions in the peripheral stat columns, as he has a pick, a fumble recovery, and a tackle for loss over his past two contests. With that being said, chasing peripheral stats is not suggested at linebacker, more so than any other position. Keep Lloyd on benches until he starts to provide consistent production.

Payton Wilson showed up again in Week 3, tallying five solos, two assists, and one fumble recovery. Wilson came back down to earth after his monster Week 2, but still managed to provide strong LB1/2 numbers. However, he played just 47 percent of the snaps, with Cole Holcomb starting over him. This drops Wilson down to the LB4/flex2 conversation as long as he keeps producing.

Rashan Gary has been downright impressive through three contests, most recently racking up three solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Rashan leads the NFL with 4.5 sacks and is going to continue to feast with Micah Parsons demanding attention on the other side. Gary is riding a three game sack streak and appears destined to set a new career high in sacks this season. Rashan needs to be counted as a DL1 option, at least until he cools down. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Holcomb was excellent in Week 3, racking up five solos, one assist, and one forced fumble. Holcomb started over Payton Wilson, and both looked better for it. Not only them, but the entire Steelers defense looked more like itself with Holcomb starting. He played just 50 percent of the snaps, while Payton Wilson played 47 percent, so there is going to be a low floor for both for the time being, regardless of who is starting. With that said, the byes are approaching, and we have a new starter in Pittsburgh. Add Holcomb wherever possible.
Bachie played just 47 percent of the snaps in Week 3, stymying his upside going forward. Keep his stashed where possible, but look elsewhere for your Week 4 LB3/4.

Derwin James went off in Week 3, tallying 10 solos, two assists, one sack, and four tackles for loss. James showed the fantasy community why IDP managers continue to hold him up as a top-three option year after year, and he should continue to be treated as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the New York Giants.

Kam Curl was excellent in Week 3, racking up six solos and three assists. Curl has recorded five or more solos in each game this season and is an easy DB1 play going forward. He should be rostered and started universally. Tap him as a DB1 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Brandon Jones was excellent in Week 3, tallying six solos, five assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Jones disappointed with his solo count through the first two weeks of the season, but stayed in the DB2 conversation thanks to his contribution in the peripheral categories. It does not look like he will become a steady DB1 option like some had hoped, but he remains an elite DB2 option, especially given plus matchups like he has in Week 4 against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Delpit finally showed up in Week 3, racking up sic solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Delpit had five solos total through the first two weeks of the season, so the production is a welcomed sign for the former DB1 candidate. Delpit has settled in as more of a DB3 than DB2 through three weeks of the season, but will be back on the DB2 map during the byes. Add and start him as a DB3 with DB2 upside for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Watts continues to impress, most recently racking up eight solos and one assist against the Carolina Panthers. Watts has recorded six or more solos in two of his three contests so far and had a pick in the other. The young safety is making plays and has entered his name into the DB2 discussion, especially with the byes fast approaching. Watts should be rostered in all competitive leagues. Start him as a DB2/3 option for Week 4.

Byard showed up in Week 3, tallying five solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Byard has five solos in two of his three contests this season and makes for a solid DB2/3 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Pitre was excellent in Week 3, reeling off three solos, one interception, and one pass defended. Pitre is playing nickel instead of safety, but has still provided solid DB3-level value for IDP managers. Treat him as such for a tasty Week 3 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Tyson Campbell was excellent in Week 3, tallying seven solos, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Camobekl has recorded three or more solos in each contest this season and is now firmly in the CB2 mix going forward. He could enter the DB3/4 conversation during the byes if he keeps up the strong play. Make the add where needed, but keep him out of lineups for Week 4 despite the plus matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Jaylen Watson showed up in Week 3, tallying five solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Watson has been stacking tackles from his outside corner spot, recording five solos twice and six or more total tackles in each contest this season. He is worth a look in deeper DB leagues and belongs in the CB1 conversation until he cools down. Make the add where needed.

Rodgers went bonkers in Week 3, going off with three solos, one interception, two forced fumbles, one fumble recovery, two passes defended, and two touchdowns. He was all over the field against the Bengals and will be one of the most talked about IDP names all week. We are advised not to chase turnovers in IDP leagues, but this was head-turning nonetheless. For his part, Rodgers has recorded three or more solos in every contest this season and had a tackle for loss in each of his first two contests. His showing put him on the CB1 map in CB leagues, but he also warrants some DB3/4 love, especially during the byes. Add Rodgers to rosters where needed, especially in deeper formats.

Jobe was impressive in Week 3, stacking nine solos, two assists, and one pass defended. He is an outside corner and had just four solos in the first two weeks of the season, so fantasy managers shouldn't get too excited here. He should be rostered in CB leagues and is worth a tap in deep 16+ team leagues, but should not be anywhere near lineups for Week 4. Look elsewhere for your Week 4 DB3/4 despite the outstanding Week 3 production.

Jamel Dean had a pick-six in Week 3 and added a solo tackle. He had six solos back in Week 1, and with another spike week on his ledger, he should be included in the CB2 conversation until he cools down. He is not much more than a DB4 in DB leagues, but could ascend quickly if he can keep up the strong IDP production.

Chau was excellent in Week 3, tallying five solos, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Chau was not much of a fantasy factor for the first two weeks of the season, but he is playing the nickel role for Carolina, so there is some upside here. Add him as a roster stash in deeper leagues, while those in shallower formats are advised to add him to watchlists. Chau does not belong in Week 4 lineups.
